  "explanation": [
    {
      "heading": "What is DNS?",
      "body": "DNS (Domain Name System) is the internet's phone book. Humans use names like `insyte.dev`; computers need IP addresses like `76.76.21.21`.\n\nDNS translates between the two. Every time you visit a website, a DNS lookup happens (unless it's cached).",
      "appearsAtStep": 0
    },
    {
      "heading": "The Recursive Resolver",
      "body": "Your ISP or a public DNS service (like `1.1.1.1` or `8.8.8.8`) runs a **recursive resolver** — it does the legwork of querying multiple name servers on your behalf and returns the final answer.\n\nWithout caching, a full lookup involves **3 round-trips** to 3 different servers.",
      "appearsAtStep": 1,
      "callout": "Cloudflare's 1.1.1.1 and Google's 8.8.8.8 are the most popular public recursive resolvers."
    },
    {
      "heading": "The DNS Hierarchy",
      "body": "DNS is organized as a tree:\n- **Root (`.`)**: 13 root server clusters worldwide, knows where all TLD servers are\n- **TLD (`.dev`, `.com`, `.io`)**: knows which authoritative NS handles each domain\n- **Authoritative NS**: the definitive answer — stores actual DNS records like A, CNAME, MX",
      "appearsAtStep": 2
    },
    {
      "heading": "Caching — The Real Performance Win",
      "body": "A cold DNS lookup can take 100–300ms. But the result is **cached** at both the resolver and browser levels.\n\nSubsequent requests to the same domain are served from cache in **< 1ms** — a 300× speedup. Most domains have a TTL (Time to Live) of 300–3600 seconds.",
      "appearsAtStep": 6,
      "callout": "This is why DNS changes take time to propagate — existing cached entries must expire first."
    },
    {
      "heading": "TTL and Cache Expiry",
      "body": "Every DNS record has a **TTL** (Time to Live) in seconds. When it hits zero, the cached entry is discarded and the next request triggers a full re-resolution.\n\nChoosing TTL is a trade-off: **low TTL** = changes propagate fast but more DNS traffic; **high TTL** = fewer queries but slow propagation.",
      "appearsAtStep": 8
    }
  ],

